{PARA 3 "" 0 "" {TEXT 322 28 " Biogeochemistry - Rate laws" }}{PARA 0 
"" 0 "" {TEXT 320 14 "Definition of " }{TEXT 279 17 "kinetic rate laws
" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 26 8 "rate.i :" }{TEXT 320 18 " array of rat
es. \n" }{TEXT 280 76 "- For equilibrium rate expression, a kinetic ra
te MUST be specified as well." }{TEXT 320 297 " It will be overwritten
 in the equilibrium section below, but you need it as space holder and
 stoichiometry. Furthermore, the steadystate module uses detailed bala
ncing method with fast kinetics. Therefore, in the example below, kf w
ill have to be defined as a rather large number and kb = kf*Keq\n" }
{TEXT 320 70 "note: all other variables are temporary and are NOT pars
ed to the ACG\n" }{TEXT 320 2 "- " }{TEXT 281 22 "conditional statemen
ts" }{TEXT 320 454 ": if a rate law depends on a conditional statement
 you need to make use of the subroutine switches.f. Example: dissoluti
on (Rd) is only to take place at undersaturation, thus  Rd= f(saturati
on). If saturation > 1, Rd>0, else Rd=0. This canbe implemented as Rd:
=k*H1*saturation, where H1 is toggled between 0 and 1. Rather than giv
ing the condition here in maple, for now you need to do this in \"swit
ches.f\", where you program the conditions for H1, e.g. " }{TEXT 282 
31 "H1=0, If (A*B/K>1) then H1 = 1." }{TEXT 320 1 "\n" }{TEXT 320 2 " \+
\n" }{TEXT 283 10 "example: \n" }{TEXT 284 61 "rate1 := 1000.*O2*hs; #
 rate law for 2O2 + HS -> SO4 + Hplus\n" }{TEXT 285 88 "rate2 := kf*hp
lus*co3 - kb*hco3; # kinetic rate law for HCO3 = CO3 + Hplus (equilibr
ium)" }}{SECT 0 {PARA 4 "" 0 "" {TEXT 324 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 4 "" 0 "
" {TEXT 324 25 " Primary redox reactions " }{HYPERLNK 17 "WWW" 4 "http
://www.geo.uu.nl/Research/Geochemistry/kb/Knowledgebook/Hetero3.pdf" "
" }{TEXT 324 0 "" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}}{PARA 4 "" 0 "" {TEXT 324 31 "
 Sulfide Re-oxidation reactions" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 
1 0 17 "rate1 := miu_max*" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "(C_S/(K_S+C_S))*" }
{MPLTEXT 1 0 22 "(C_O2/(K_O2+C_O2))*X_S" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 2 ";\n" }
{MPLTEXT 1 0 9 "rate2 := " }{MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "nu_anox*miu_max*" }
{MPLTEXT 1 0 57 "(C_S/(K_S+C_S))*(C_NO/(K_NO+C_NO))*(K_i_O2/(K_i_O2+C_
O2))" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 4 "*X_S" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 2 ";\n" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 9 "ra
te3 := " }{MPLTEXT 1 0 7 "b_S*X_S" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 1 ";" }}{PARA 11 "" 1
 "" {XPPMATH 20 ">I&rate1G6\"*.I(miu_maxGF$\"\"\"I$C_SGF$F',&I$K_SGF$F
'F(F'!\"\"I%C_O2GF$F',&I%K_O2GF$F'F,F'F+I$X_SGF$F'" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 ""
 {XPPMATH 20 ">I&rate2G6\"*4I(nu_anoxGF$\"\"\"I(miu_maxGF$F'I$C_SGF$F'
,&I$K_SGF$F'F)F'!\"\"I%C_NOGF$F',&I%K_NOGF$F'F-F'F,I'K_i_O2GF$F',&F0F'
I%C_O2GF$F'F,I$X_SGF$F'" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 ">I&rate3G6\"*
&I$b_SGF$\"\"\"I$X_SGF$F'" }}}}}{SECT 0 {PARA 3 "" 0 "" {TEXT 322 33 "
 Biogeochemistry - Stoichiometry\n" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 320 46 "St
oichiometry of the biogeochemical reactions\n" }{TEXT 26 9 "d.sp.dt :"
 }{TEXT 320 66 " rates of change of sp due to the sum of biogeochemica
l reactions\n" }{TEXT 320 44 "note that rateX must be referred to as r
X  \n" }{TEXT 320 2 " \n" }{TEXT 286 9 "example:\n" }{TEXT 287 16 "dO2
dt := -2*r1;\n" }{TEXT 288 14 "dhco3dt = -r2;" }{TEXT 320 1 " " }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 22 "delstd := 0.0112372 ;\n" }
{MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "s_dens := 2.5 ;\n" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 48 "#SD := 1.0e3 * s
_dens * (1.0 - por(j)) / por(j);" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 0 "" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "
" {XPPMATH 20 ">I'delstdG6\"$\"'sB6!\"(" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 
20 ">I's_densG6\"$\"#D!\"\"" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 320 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 1 "d" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 3 "C_S" }
{MPLTEXT 1 0 17 "dt := -r1 - r2 ;\n" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 25 "dX_Sdt := r1 + \+
r2 - r3 ;\n" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 1 "d" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "C_O2dt := -r1 ;\n" 
}{MPLTEXT 1 0 1 "d" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 4 "C_NO" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "dt := 0.8
*r2;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 ">I'dC_SdtG6\",&I#r1GF$!\"\"I#r2G
F$F'" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 ">I'dX_SdtG6\",(I#r1GF$\"\"\"I#r2
GF$F'I#r3GF$!\"\"" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 ">I(dC_O2dtG6\",$I#r
1GF$!\"\"" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 ">I(dC_NOdtG6\",$I#r2GF$$\"
\")!\"\"" }}}}{SECT 0 {PARA 3 "" 0 "" {TEXT 322 29 " Biogeochemistry -
 Equilibria" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 320 41 "Specification of equilibr
ium constraints\n" }{TEXT 26 10 "eqrxnsId :" }{TEXT 320 75 " set of ki
netic reactions which are overuled by a thermodynamic constraint " }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 26 20 "equilibriumseqns[i] " }{TEXT 320 42 ": Eq
uilibrium constraint for reaction i  \n" }{TEXT 320 1 "\n" }{TEXT 289 
9 "example:\n" }{TEXT 290 20 "eqrxnID := [r2,rX];\n" }{TEXT 291 44 "eq
uilibriumeqns[1] := hplus*co3 - Keq*hco3;\n" }{TEXT 292 26 "equilibriu
meqns[2] := ...;" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "eqrxnId \+
:= [] ;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 ">I(eqrxnIdG6\"7\"" }}}{EXCHG 
{PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 33 "#equilibriumeqns[1] := b - k3*c ;" 
}}}}{SECT 0 {PARA 3 "" 0 "" {TEXT 322 29 " Biogeochemistry - Parameter
s" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 32 41 "Values of rates constants and parame
ters " }{TEXT 320 1 "\n" }{TEXT 320 82 "In this section, all parameter
s defined in section 'Rate laws' should be defined.\n" }{TEXT 26 6 "np
aram" }{TEXT 320 34 ": number of parameters to define \n" }{TEXT 320 
21 "The list is given by " }{TEXT 26 8 "bio_name" }{TEXT 320 26 "; the
 values collected in " }{TEXT 26 8 "bio_val." }{TEXT 320 1 "\n" }{TEXT
 320 60 "note that for double precision, 10 should be written as 10.\n
" }{TEXT 320 1 "\n" }{TEXT 293 9 "example:\n" }{TEXT 294 11 "nparam:=4
;\n" }{TEXT 295 30 "bio_name:=[kmo2hs,kf,kb,Keq];\n" }{TEXT 296 18 "vk
f :=1.0*10^(5);\n" }{TEXT 297 22 "vKeq:=1.0*10^(-10.4);\n" }{TEXT 298 
16 "vkb :=vkf*vKeq;\n" }{TEXT 299 30 "bio_val:=[1000.,vkf,vkb,vKeq];" 
}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 320 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 320 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "nparam := 7 ;" }}{PARA 11 ""
 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 ">I'nparamG6\"\"\"(" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 13 "bio_name := [" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 9 "miu_max, " }{MPLTEXT 
1 0 40 "b_S, K_S, K_O2, K_NO, K_i_O2, nu_anox] ;" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 1 " " 
}}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 ">I)bio_nameG6\"7)I(miu_maxGF$I$b_SGF$I
$K_SGF$I%K_O2GF$I%K_NOGF$I'K_i_O2GF$I(nu_anoxGF$" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 ">
 " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 71 "bio_val := [6/86400, 0.62/86400, 0.3, 0.00625
, 0.0357, 0.003125, 0.8] ;" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 2 " \n" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 ">I(bio_valG6\"7)#\"\"\"\"&+W\"$\"+Ef#f<(!#:$\"\"$!\"\"$\"
$D'!\"&$\"$d$!\"%$\"%DJ!\"'$\"\")F." }}}{SECT 0 {PARA 3 "" 0 "" {TEXT 
322 8 "Switches" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 236 55 "Switches can be used \+
in the rate equations. Specify in " }{TEXT 26 9 "nswitches" }{TEXT 
236 114 ", how many switches are in use, name them and define the swit
ch expressions. The switch names must also appear in " }{TEXT 26 8 "bi
o_name" }{TEXT 236 179 " and must be assigned a dummy value there. The
 switch equals 1 if the switch expression is >0, 0 otherwise. To refer
ence the coordinates in the domain, use x_pos, y_pos and z_pos." }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 16 "nswitches := 0 ;" }}{PARA 11
 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 ">I*nswitchesG6\"\"\"!" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 
"" {MPLTEXT 1 0 26 "switchlist := [sw1, sw2] ;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 ">I+switchlistG6\"7$I$sw1GF$I$sw2GF$" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 ">
 " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 74 "switchcrit := [x(j) - (depthmax/(2.0*Ncol-Col
_size/2.0)), 1.0e-2 - x(j)] ;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 ">I+swit
chcritG6\"7$,&-I\"xGF$6#I\"jGF$\"\"\"*&I)depthmaxGF$F+,&I%NcolGF$$\"#?
!\"\"I)Col_sizeGF$$!+++++]!#5F2F2,&$\"#5!\"$F+F'F2" }}}{PARA 3 "" 0 ""
 {TEXT 322 0 "" }}}}{SECT 0 {PARA 3 "" 0 "" {TEXT 322 32 " Transport -
 Molecular Diffusion" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 320 54 "Specification of
 the molecular diffusion coefficients\n" }{TEXT 26 9 "diffdata:" }
{TEXT 320 63 " molecular diffusion coefficient at 0 degree celsius (cm
^2/yr)\n" }{TEXT 26 11 "alphadata: " }{TEXT 320 59 "temperature depend
ence of the diffusion coefficient (1/K) \n" }{TEXT 320 88 "the in situ
 molecular diffusion coefficient, corrected for tortuosity is calculat
ed as:\n" }{TEXT 320 75 "D(T,sal) = [(0.95-0.001*sal)* D(T=0,sal=0)*(1
 + muc*T[C])]/(1-ln(por^2))  \n" }{TEXT 300 9 "example:\n" }{TEXT 301 
37 "diffdata := [100., 304.,0.,0.,100.];\n" }{TEXT 302 38 "alphadata:=
 [0.006, 0.04,0.,0.,.0.05];" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 
24 "diffdata := [1,1,1,1] ;\n" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 24 "alphadata := [0,0,0,0
] ;" }{MPLTEXT 1 0 2 " \n" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 ">I)diffdata
G6\"7&\"\"\"F&F&F&" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 ">I*alphadataG6\"7&
\"\"!F&F&F&" }}}}{SECT 0 {PARA 3 "" 0 "" {TEXT 322 32 " Transport - Bo
undary Conditions" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 320 71 "Specification of up
per and lower boundary conditions for each species.\n" }{TEXT 320 21 "
There are 3 options \n" }{TEXT 320 42 "0. known concentration (Dirichl
et, M/L^3)\n" }{TEXT 320 51 "1. known concentration gradient (Neumann,
 M/L^3*L)\n" }{TEXT 320 63 "2. known total (diffusive and advective) f
lux (Robin, M/L^2/T)\n" }{TEXT 320 346 "technical note: option 1 and 2
 involve ghost points outside the domain. If the mixing parameters var
y with depth, one needs to assign a mixing intensities at the ghost po
ints. By default this is done by linear extrapolation. To ovrwrite thi
s, the user has to edit gridsetup.f and advdiffcoeff.f (both at the bo
ttom; explanations are given there)\n" }{TEXT 26 8 "type_up:" }{TEXT 
320 90 " array defining the type of condition for each species at the \+
upper boundary (0, 1 or 2) \n" }{TEXT 26 11 "bnddata_up:" }{TEXT 303 
1 " " }{TEXT 320 60 "array containing the values specified at the uppe
r boundary." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 26 10 "type_down:" }{TEXT 320 77 
" array defining the type of condition for each species at the lower b
oundary " }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT 26 13 "bnddata_down:" }{TEXT 304 1 "
 " }{TEXT 320 60 "array containing the values specified at the upper b
oundary." }}{PARA 214 "" 0 "" {TEXT 26 0 "" }{TEXT 305 1 "\n" }{TEXT 
